For spiritual wisdom consists not of the illumination of the intellect alone, neither of the renovation of the affec- tions alone, but of both conjointly. From which and similar places, it is manifest, that this wisdom, although as to its essence it is a certain perfection of the intellect, yet as to its matter and use, is also practical and moral.
